This is a project for BIE-SW1 and BIE-SP1 courses on the summer semester 2022/2023. Our goal is to build or modify a web application which helps us to manage a household easily. Some of the functionalities, that we are expecting to offer, include checking, updating and tracking information from the household that can be useful for the house members. In this part, we will mostly focus in the analysis of the idea and describe all the processes of the project. Detailed Features of the application: 1. Sharing the Household: The owner of a household can invite as many people as he/she wants to his household management system, and manage/organize the house together. He can also remove members or leave the household. 2. Stock Management: The members of a household can keep track of any items in their house. The app will remind them whenever any item is about to be expired, or out of stock. Members can also search categorized products for example, they can search for milk which will show them how many type and how much milk they have left with expiration date. 3. Energy Consumption Tracking: The members of a household can upload their weekly/monthly/yearly amount of energy consumption to track their usage. They can also set up remainders for uploading energy consumption bills. They can organize their bills and compare their usage with different time period. 4. Maintenance Planning: The owner of a household can create maintenance planning remainder for devices in the household for a specific time period(1 month/6 months/1 year) with a deadline. The maintenance tasks can be assigned to assignee person(either the owner or any other member of the household).

We analyzed our project and decided that it will have two main processes:

The owner of a household can create maintenance planning task with a deadline and assign it to assignee (either the owner or any other member of the household). After finishing the maintenance task, the assignee will mark the task as resolved. Then if the owner is satisfied, they can close the task as done. Otherwise, the owner can update the task details and again reassign it. But if the deadline passes but task is not assigned or resolved. Then the user can check the task and close it as not done or reassign it.

Invitation process: An Owner of a household can Send an invitation to other users who are logged in the app. Then the Invited user will Check the invitation and decide either to Join the household or Reject joining the household. However, if the Invited user doesn't accept the invitation in 24 hours, then the invitation will be automatically rejected by the System.

Requirements that are well thought through and clearly documented are essential to any successful software engineering project. There are two main different types of system requirements that should be gathered by those working on software projects. System requirements can be categorized as either functional requirements or non functional requirements.

Category Filters: Members should be able to search for items based on their category. This can help them find specific types of items more quickly.
Name Filters: Members should also be able to search for items by name. Hierarchy Filters: If the household management system includes a hierarchy of locations, Members can search for all items located in different locations based on their hierarchy.

When a Logged User creates a new household, they become the Owner of that household by default. This means that they have the highest level of permissions and can perform all actions related to the household.
The Owner can also modify the household's details, including the title and description.
If a user is no longer participating in the household or needs to be removed for any reason, the Owner can remove them from the household. This will revoke their access to the household's resources and data. To remove a user, the Owner will need to go to the household's member list and look for the relevant options.
Finally, if the household is no longer needed or becomes inactive, the Owner can delete the household. This will remove all data related to the household, so it's important to be sure before taking this step. To delete a household, the Owner will need to go to the household settings or options menu and look for the relevant options.
Members should be able to compare the energy consumption values between two dates. This could be useful for identifying changes in energy usage over time.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: FR1.2: Join/ Leave/ Invite to household

UML:TaggedValue.value:
Sending invitation: The Owner can invite other users to join the household. To do this, they'll typically need to provide the email addresses or usernames of the users they want to invite. Once invited, these users will receive an email or notification with link to join the household.
Joining a household: If any user receive an invitation to join a household from owner, they should be able to do so as long as you are a Logged User. The invitation may come in the form of an email or notification, and it should include link to join the household. Once you've joined the household, you should be able to access the household's resources available.
Leaving a household: A Member of a household and no longer wish to participate, he/she should be able to leave the household. This will typically revoke their access to the household's resources and data.
Leaving a household as an Owner: If the Owner of a household and no longer wish to manage it, they should be able to leave the household. This will typically transfer ownership to another Member of the household. If there are no other Members, it will delete the household.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: FR3.2: Notify owner and assignee about changes in the maintenance task

UML:TaggedValue.value: When a Member has been assigned a maintenance task, they should receive notifications about the task, including when it was assigned, any updates made to the task, and when it is due. This helps ensure that Members are aware of their responsibilities and can complete tasks in a timely manner.

Modify Quantities: Members should be able to edit the quantities of items in the household. This means that they can increase or decrease the amount of a specific item that is available, depending on the needs of the household.
Modify Stock Management: Members should be able to create, edit, or delete items in the household. This means that they have more control over the inventory of the household, and can make sure that everything is up-to-date and accurately reflects what is available. For example, a Member with this access right could create a new item in the household's inventor.
Expiration Dates: Members can set expiration dates for each item in the household, and get notifications when items are about to expire so that they can be discarded or restocked. By setting expiration dates and getting notifications, Members can help ensure that there is not expired item in the household inventory.

Owner Access: Only the Owner of a household has the ability to create, edit and delete maintenance tasks. This helps ensure that the household's maintenance schedule is managed in a consistent and organized way.
Task Creation: When creating a new maintenance task, the Owner can specify details such as the task name, description, expiry period, start date, end date, repetition frequency, generation date, and assignee. The system will use the expiry period and repetition frequency to generate new tasks with new generation date, assignee.
Assigning maintenance task: The Owner can assign maintenance tasks to any Member of the household. When a task is assigned, the owner and the assignee will receive a notification via email.
Task Completion: The assignee of a maintenance task can mark the task as resolved when finished. However, they cannot edit or delete the task itself.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: FR1.3: Access rights of participants of the household group.

UML:TaggedValue.value:
Owner: The Owner has all the access rights and manages the access rights of the members from the household. The Owner can transfer ownership or share data to other members or completely remove the household. Owner can also send invitations to users to join the household. Additionally, he/she will have the ability to modify the household settings, including the household's name and description.
Members: Members of a household have more limited access rights than the Owner, but still have important permissions. Members can add or modify locations, sub-locations, and items in the household, as long as they have been given permission to do so by the Owner. They can also participate in maintenance tasks, such as checking off completed tasks or adding new ones.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: FR4.3: Notify user about the need to fill energy consumption data

UML:TaggedValue.value:
Members will should receive notifications to remind them to add new energy consumption values.
Additionally, all Members should be able to browse the energy consumption values, including visualizations of consumption data and the ability to compare consumption in different periods of time.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: FR2.3: Notify user about the expired or out of stock item

UML:TaggedValue.value:
Stock Management Notifications: Members will receive notifications when items are running low or out of stock. This can be set up to send notifications when an item's quantity has reached 0. When a notification is triggered, member can remove or replenish the item.
Expiration Date Notifications: Similarly, Members will receive notifications via email a certain period of time prior to an item's expiration date. When a notification is triggered, member can get rid of the expired item. After that, they can remove the item or replenish the item.

Members should be able to add new energy consumption values to the system. This could involve entering data for the amount of energy used by the household, as well as any relevant information such as the date and time of the consumption.
Other Members should also be able to view the energy consumption data that has been saved in the system. This could be useful for tracking energy usage over time, identifying trends or patterns in usage, and finding ways to reduce energy consumption.
The web application is realized using color green, white, and red.
The web application should be able to handle over 100 users at the same time with response time less than 3 seconds.
The web application also should notify the users even when the user is not using the application. The notification will be sent to the email address which was used to sign up.
The web application will be deployed using docker.

The web application is planed to be developed by Java Spring Boot framework, so it uses Thyme leaf for server part. The web application can be accessed using a browser, - Google Chrome (version 110 or higher) - Firefox (version 110 or higher) - Edge (version 106 or higher) - Safari (version 16 or higher) - Others (supports TLS 1.2 or 1.3 and they are enabled also JavaScript enabled).
The application is scalable with the users screen size and resolution.

Since the application should store a lot of information stable and safe, we should use a relational database. We will have to handle large amount of user data. Therefore we should consider a database which is scalable, supports JSON, XML variety of predefined functions, semi structured data, structured data.

The ConsumptionTrack entity represents a time period that a user can define manually to help with assigning consumption values. This time period is used to track the quantity of a specific resource that a user has consumed over a certain period of time. The ConsumptionTrack entity contains several attributes that are used to manage and track the user's consumption of a specific resource. For example, the entity has attributes for the start and end dates of the consumption period.
End date of the consumption Tracking.
Start date of the consumption tracking.

The main goal of the household is to maintain the amount of items and the quantity of each, that he have in a specific moment. An Item should have a title, a description and a quantity. Optionally, we can add an expiration date in the case of the food products and a picture to identify visually the product. We can have more than one item with the same title but a different expiration date which is represented by item stock.
Title is a name of the item
An item can be in no category, or in more than one (0..*). And a category has to group at least one item to exist, and a maximum of N items (1..N).

The User entity contains various attributes that are used to manage the user's account and track their status. For example, the entity has a unique identifier that is used to look up the user in the system's database. It also has attributes for the user's email address, password, and other account information, first name, last name,, username. The role attribute of the User entity specifies the user's role within the application. Users can have either a User role or an Owner role. The roles are represented in membership class.
This attribute indicates if user is acive or incative.

A Category represents a group of item that have similar characteristics. It must be unique. A category has the following attributes: a title of the item that this category is grouping. A owner of a household will be able to create categories while inserting or editing items. Members can select from existing categories. Categories will also be unique for each household.
Title is the name of the category.

A consumption must be added manually by a user and it can be of different ResourceType (electricity, water, gas...) every time period. Therefore, it is composed of a start (date and time), end (date and time), quantity consumed and additionally the user can add the bill, so that the rest of the users can take a look to the bill in future situations. For each record there will be deadline. In case member does not upload the record, it will send notification email to the member.
bill is amount to be paid for defined period of time
deadline for adding the consumption record
generationDate of the consumption record is the day when record is started
quantity_consumed is amount of resource(energy, water, gas and electricity) consumed.

A household is where everything located: tasks, storage,energy consumption tracking. Household is a physical space. It has address and a name(which owner gives to it)
The HouseHold entity represents a physical space where everything related to a user's household is located, including tasks, storage, and energy consumption tracking. A HouseHold is identified by a unique name, which is assigned by the owner of the household, and has an associated address that can be used to locate it.
id is unique identifier of the household

Item Stock is a unique physical representation of an item. Item can have many copies. Every copy can be identified with copy_id and has their one title,expiration and quantity. This entity is used to identify the same item in different locations or to track different copies of the same item that are owned by different users. This allows users to manage their inventory of items more effectively and to keep track of which items are available in which locations.
Amount represents the quantity of copies of item
copy_id is the unique identifier of items in different location.
Description of the copy of the item
expirationDate is the date when item expires.
unit is identifier of measurement unit(kg, l, p).

For one created maintenance task, there can be one to many repetitive tasks, which will have different generation date, assignee, deadline, resolve, state, closing date. Task class represents each individual repetitive tasks.
Each instance of the Task class has its own set of attributes, including a generation date, which indicates when the task was scheduled to be completed. It also has an assignee, which is the person or team responsible for completing the task. The deadline for the task is set based on the schedule for the task, and can be different for each instance. By using the Task class to manage these ongoing tasks, the system provides a way to track and manage maintenance activities, ensuring that they are completed on time and in a consistent manner.
Attribute deadline has variable type Date. Deadline is special date until which task has to be completed by members. It consists of current_generation_Date+deadline_period
current_generation_Date is a date for which each new task will be generated.
it is the generation period for next repetitive task, if next date passes end_date, it will stop generating task.
State represents current state of the task. It can be not closed or closed.

The Location entity represents an address or physical location for an item that is located within a household. Locations can have title, title description, unique identifier for identifying the household it is located. One location can have many sub locations which will be identified same way.
Description is written description of the location
id is a unique identifier of the location
Title is a name of the location

A ResourceType is a kind of data that let us identify the resource details that was consumed. Each ResourceType is identified by a title and a price per unit, the unit represent m<sup>3</sup> in the case of water and gas, kW in the case of electricity. This helps to ensure that consumption records are accurately recorded and can be compared across different periods of time and users.
price represents cost per unit (to be paid for 1 m<sup>3</sup> in case of water and gas, and 1 kW for electricity)
title represents the name of resource (gas, water and electricity)

A Maintenance Task needs to be created by a owner of a household and it can be assigned to owner, assignee or to nobody. A maintenance task represent a small amount of work that needs to be done in a specific amount of time, therefore it is composed of a title, a description, reporter of the issue, startDate, repetition days(after how many days it should regenerate) so that the assigned user can know what exactly should do, and a end (date and time) which represents until the day task should generate repetitively. If the task has state resolved(by assignee/owner) and closed(owner), it will generate another ticket for next generation date with new deadline, state, assignee, closing_date(represented by MaintenanceTask class).
end_date is the date until which task will be regenerated.
frequency is the amount of time period (day/week/month) inserted by user for repetitive task
it will save days/ week/ month/ year which will be used for repetition of tasks.
start_date is starting date of the task.
Title represents a name of the task.
A user doesn't need to create any task, but can also create unlimited tasks (0..*). A task needs to be created by just one user (1..1). Task can be only created by owner of the Household.
It represents different possible states of the maintenance task.

Membership is an access level of the user to the household. Without membership user cannot be in a household. Owner of the household is top level access to that household. creation date of the membership is the day of creating household(in case of the owner) or the day of the accepting the invitation to the household(for other members). membership_role is the permission level of the member.
creationDate is the date of creation of membership of a household
id is unique identifier of each membership
membership_role indicates level of permission user has. It can be owner or member.
MembershipStatus represents states of membership in a household(active or removed).

The VerificationToken class is a crucial component of systems that require user authentication and authorization. For example, the token has a unique identifier that is used to look it up in the system's database. It also has an expiration date, which is set when the token is generated and used to ensure that the token is only valid for a limited period of time.

The ResourceType entity serves as a data holder for the data about resource types stored in a persistent storage. A ResourceType is a type of energy that is used in the households.

@OneToMany(mappedBy = "item") private List<Copy> copies; @ManyToOne private Category category;

The Authority entity serves as a data holder for the data about authority stored in a persistent storage. Authority is a level of right of each member of the households. For example, owner. A single membership has to have one kind of authority, and one authority can be assigned to several memberships.

The Membership entity serves as a data holder for the data of memberships stored in a persistent storage. Membership is a connection of a household and a user. Many memberships can belong to one household, one authority, and one user.

The Task entity serves as a data holder for the data of Tasks stored in a persistent storage. Task is an assignment that a member of a household creates and may assign to one of the household members. A single Task must have one author and zero to many asignee.

The Location entity serves as a data holder for the data about locations in the households stored in a persistent storage. There can be several locations in one household. For each location, there can be several copies of an item. Each location have sub locations to be more specified.
The User entity serves as a data holder for the data of users stored in a persistent storage. A single User can have many memberships but one membership per one household.

The Copy entity serves as a data holder for the data of copies of each item stored in a persistent storage. Copy is an actual piece of an item. A single item can have many copies of it, and one copy can be from only one item.
@ManyToOne private Item item; @ManyToOne private Location location;

The Category entity serves as a data holder for the data about category stored in a persistent storage. Category is for sorting the items in the household, so that the user can find and see the items efficiently. A single category can have many items, but one item should belong to only one category. The ConsumptionRecord entity serves as a data holder for the data of records of energy consumption stored in a persistent storage.
The HouseHold entity serves as a data holder for the data about household stored in a persistent storage. A single household can have many memberships, locations, and consumption tracks.

In this chapter, the realization of some of the use cases of the Household is described, showing the communication of classes of the web application.
Class model for the add Category.

Once the owner requests to add a new category on the web site (/addCategory), the HTTP Server calls a method addCategory on an instance CategoryController. Then CategoryController calls a method findHouseholdById on an instance householdService to get the household which contains the id. After that, with that household, mainCategory as null, CategoryController calls a method addCategory on an instance categoryServicve which sets the details from the CategoryCreationDTO, then saves the data to database by calling save method and passes the category which will return a Category. After that, CategoryController calls isOwner on the instance of authorizationService which returns boolean value, and send the result list to model to show them. It also send the household and houseoldId to model to show them. After all the processes, the web site shows the /category (the category View) page to the user.
Class model for the add Maintenance.

Once the owner requests to add a new maintenance on the web site (/addMaintenance), the HTTP Server calls a method getAddMaintenancePage on an instance MaintenanceController. Then MaintenanceController calls a method findAllMembership on an instance membershipService to get all the membership from database. Then MaintenanceController calls a method findHouseholdById on an instance householdService to get the household which contains the id. After that, with that household, MaintenanceCreationDTO, MaintenanceController calls a method addMaintenance on an instance maintenanceServicve which sets the details from the MaintenanceCreationDTO, then saves the data to database by calling save method and passes the Maintenance which will return a Maintenance. Then MaintenanceController calls a method maintenanceEmailProcessing on an class maintenanceConfig to send email to reporter and assignee. Then MaintenanceController calls a method publishEvent on an instance eventPublisher to save the inventoryChange to Logs. After that, MaintenanceController calls isOwner on the instance of authorizationService which returns boolean value, and send the result list to model to show them. It also send the maintenance(all the maintenance in the household), household and houseoldId to model to show them. After all the processes, the web site shows the /maintenance (the maintenance View) page to the user.
Class model for the add Maintenance Task When Button Clicked.

Once the owner requests to add a new maintenance Task on the web site (/addMaintenanceTask), the HTTP Server calls a method addMaintenanceWhenGenerateButton on an instance MaintenanceTaskController. Then MaintenanceController calls a method findHouseholdById on an instance householdService to get the household which contains the id. Then MaintenanceController calls a method findMaintenanceById on an instance maintenanceService to get the maintenance which contains the id. After that, with that household, Maintenance, MaintenanceTaskController calls a method addMaintenanceTask on an instance maintenanceTaskServicve which sets the details from the Maintenance, calculates possible startDate, Deadline, then saves the data to database by calling save method and passes the MaintenanceTask which will return a MaintenanceTask. Then MaintenanceTaskController calls a method maintenanceEmailProcessing on an class maintenanceConfig to send email to reporter and assignee. Then MaintenanceController calls a method publishEvent on an instance eventPublisher to save the inventoryChange to Logs. After that, MaintenanceTaskController calls isOwner on the instance of authorizationService which returns boolean value, and send the result list to model to show them. It also send the maintenanceTask(all possible maintenanceTasks in maintenance), maintenance(found Maintenance), household and houseoldId to model to show them. After all the processes, the web site shows the /maintenance/maintenanceId (the maintenance Details) page to the user.

It describes a physical structure of a system such as definition of servers, devices, or execution environments by the distribution of system components to physical nodes. The Household consists of a central database located on a central server located in the cloud. Also, the Web Application created as a Java Spring boot web application is running on the same server. The members, the guests and the owner can use an internet browser on their own computers to use.
Database model shows the structure of database schema using tables, columns, constraints, data types. This is not a complete schema, but mainly focused on the funtionalities we have been implemented.
In our case, the packages can be sorted in this way: Presentation Layer includes controller and security. Business Layer includes service. Data Layer includes datamodel and repository.
This is the design model of our system.
Repository class for management of user entities in the database.

Once an Anonymous User requests to sign up on the web site(/signup), the HTTP Server calls a method signup on an instance of UserController class, userContoller. Then UserController calls a method getPassword on an instance of User class, user, to get the password. Once it returns the password, UserController encode it on the instance of PasswordEncoder, and send it back to the instance user to set the password on the instance of User. After that, UserController calls a method createOrUpdateUser on an instance userService and UserService will pass the User to save it in the data base through an instance userRepository. After all the processes, the web site shows the login page to the user.

Once a User requests to search a user or a list of users with a search term, the method searchForUser is called on an instance userController of the class UserController. Then UserController calls a method findUserBySearchTerm on an instance of UserService class, userService, to get the list of Users who contains the search term. Then UserService call a method searchByUsername on the instance of UserRepository to actually access the database and get the list of users. Once UserController receives the list of users, it calls methods addAttribute on model instance to show the users and the household ID. After all the processes, the web site shows the invite-user page to the user.

Once an User requests to add a new household on the web site (/addhousehold), the HTTP Server calls a method createHousehold on an instance householdController. Then HouseholdController calls a method getName on an instance authentication to get the username of the person who requests. After that, with that username, HouseController calls a method fidnUserByUsername on an instance userService to get the user. Then HouseController create a new instance membership and calls a method setStatus on it to change the status to Active, and it calls a method createMembership on an instance membershipService. Then it add a new Membership using method call addMembership on both of instances user and household. And Save the Membership on the database by calling save method on MembershipRepository. After that, HouseholdController calls getMemberships on the instance of User twice with filter PENDING and ACTIVE and send the result list to model to show them. After all the processes, the web site shows the welcome (the household management) page to the user.
